For binary classification (depressed / not)
XGBoost or LightGBM would be my top pick — they handle mixed data types, missing values, and class imbalance really well, which is exactly what you'll have after merging 4 datasets from different sources. Fast to train too.
Random Forest is a solid baseline and gives you feature importance for free, which is super useful here to understand which questions matter most — important for when you build the interface later.
Logistic Regression is worth including as a sanity baseline. If your fancy models don't beat it significantly, something's wrong with your features.

For severity prediction (0→4 scale)
This is an ordinal regression problem — the classes have an order (mild < moderate < severe), so standard multiclass classification ignores that structure. Two good approaches:
XGBoost with ordinal objective handles this natively. Alternatively you can treat it as plain multiclass and it still works decently.
Ordinal Logistic Regression (mord library in Python) is the statistically clean choice if you want to respect the ordinal nature properly.

My suggested approach for your project:
Since you're at ESME in AI majeur, I'd go with this stack:

Random Forest as baseline (interpretable, explainable)
XGBoost as your main model (best performance)
A simple Neural Network with sklearn or PyTorch as a third comparison point

Then use SHAP values to explain which features drive predictions — this is really powerful for a mental health context and would make your project stand out (herausstechen — to stand out).

One important thing to keep in mind: depression datasets tend to be imbalanced (fewer depressed samples). Make sure to use class_weight='balanced' or SMOTE oversampling, otherwise your model will just predict "not depressed" for everyone and still get 80% accuracy on paper.
